Overview.Summary: The 2018 Eurovision Song Contest will take place in Lisbon, Portugal on May 12 (1) with a total of 43 countries participating (6). Betting odds have predicted Cyprus (2) and Israel (3,4,9,10) to win, with Netta Barzilai representing Israel with the song "Toy" (6,7,8,10). The 2018 winner will be the first time Israel has won the Eurovision Song Contest (3,4,7).

Overview.Summary: Eurovision Song Contest 2018 took place in Lisbon, Portugal (6). Israel won with the song "Toy" (2,3,4), performed by Netta Barzilai (8,9) and scored 529 points (3). The event was broadcasted on August 23, 2018 (10) and was attended by various countries (5). The winner was announced as Netta Barzilai (2,4,6,8,10) from Israel (2,3,4,8,10).

Timeline.Text: Lisbon is officially announced as the host city of the Eurovision Song Contest 2018.
The official website for the Eurovision Song Contest 2018 in Lisbon is launched, featuring contestant profiles and news updates.
The Portuguese travel agency Viajar Tours announces successful charter sales to take tourists to Lisbon for the Eurovision Song Contest.
The bookmakers have three favored countries to win the Eurovision Song Contest 2018, including Israel.
The voting and points for the Eurovision Song Contest 2018 in Lisbon are released, with Israel ultimately winning with the song 'Toy'.

Alexander Rybak, who won the Eurovision Song Contest in 2009 and represented Norway in 2018, shows his support for the Eurovision Young Musicians competition, which was broadcasted during the 2018 Eurovision Song Contest in Lisbon.

Overview.Summary: In 2018, the Eurovision Song Contest was held in Lisbon, Portugal (3,6), and Finland did not qualify to compete in the contest (1). The Eurovision Song Contest is an annual music competition (2) and was first held in 1956 (7). ABBA from Sweden won in 1974 (9). The 2018 winner was Netta Barzilai from Israel with her song "Toy" (7,6). However, according to bookmakers, Finland was one of the top three favorites to win (6). The 2017 Best Europa stamp - Jury prize was awarded to Finland (8).

Timeline.Text: The official logo and slogan for Eurovision Song Contest 2018 is revealed in a ceremony in Lisbon.
Finland's entry for Eurovision Song Contest 2018 is chosen through the national selection process.
The results of the 2017 Best Europa stamp - Jury prize are announced, with Finland winning the prize.
The Eurovision Song Contest 2011 is held in Düsseldorf, Germany, with Finland placing third.
Finnish singer Laura Rizzotto covers Portugal's Eurovision Song Contest 2018 entry.
The winner of Eurovision Song Contest 2018, Netta Barzilai from Israel, is announced.
ABBA wins the 19th Eurovision Song Contest with their song Waterloo.
The Finnish entry for Eurovision Song Contest 2015, Something Better, is revealed.
Finland is placed 3rd at the Eurovision Song Contest 1974, with the song Waterloo.
The results of the 2018 Eurovision Song Contest are announced, with Finland not making into the top 10.

Overview.Summary: The Eurovision Song Contest 2018, which was held in Lisbon, Portugal, had its first day of rehearsals on April 29 (1) and took place on May 12 (8). The theme "Forever" was present in Latvian contestant Laura Rizzotto's cover of "Dream On" (5). The winner of the Contest in 2018 was Israel with the song "Toy" (9). Host and actress Katie Boyle, Lady Saunders, who passed away at the age of 91, had also hosted the Eurovision Song Contest in the 1960s and 1970s (8).

Timeline.Text: The first day of Rehearsals at the 2018 Eurovision Song Contest takes place in Lisbon, Portugal.
Celebrated Eurovision Song Contest host and actress Katie Boyle passes away at the age of 91.
The Eurovision Song Contest is held in Lisbon, Portugal.
Latvian contestant Laura Rizzotto releases a cover of the winning contest song, 'Forever', by Portuguese contestant Salvador Sobral.

Overview.Summary: In the 2018 Eurovision Song Contest (9), the UK's act Engelbert Humperdinck finished last, while Sunstroke Project from Moldova (8) achieved their best result in the competition (8). However, other countries such as Austria, Finland, Norway, Portugal, and Sweden boycotted the contest (9). The show has been a tradition since 1956 (10) but has been met with mixed responses, with some countries displeased with the results of previous years (9). Social media has been used to discuss the event, with a Twitter preview show for the 2018 Eurovision Song Contest (8) and a hashtag dedicated to spreading love for the event (#SpreadLoveIn3Words) (2). Betting odds have also been available for the event (1).

Overview.Summary: The Eurovision Song Contest 2018 (1,2,5,6,8,9,10) took place in Lisbon, Portugal (2,3,9). Netta Barzilai from Israel won with the song "Toy" (5,6,10). The competition was broadcast live on TV (7,9) and has been a yearly event since 1956 (8). Will Ferrell is writing and starring in a movie about the Eurovision Song Contest (8).

Timeline.Text: China's most popular TV channel is barred from airing the Eurovision Song Contest.
The Eurovision Song Contest takes place in Lisbon, Portugal.
Actor Pedro Granger receives a dream gift from RTP as he prepares to host the Eurovision Song Contest.
Netflix announces a new comedy movie about the Eurovision Song Contest.
Eurovision fans predict Cyprus, represented by singer Eleni Foureira, will win the 2018 contest.
Actor Will Ferrell announces he will write and star in a new movie based on the Eurovision Song Contest.
Norwegian violinist Daniel Lozakovich, who will represent Norway in the 2018 Eurovision Song Contest, is a guest performer at the 2009 contest.
The Eurovision Live Concert 2018 takes place in Setúbal, Portugal, with performances from past Eurovision contestants.

Overview.Summary: The Eurovision Song Contest 2018, held in Lisbon, Portugal, was won by Netta Barzilai from Israel with her song "Toy" (2,3,20). The contest saw a record-breaking 43 countries participate (4), including first-time entrant San Marino (1). The event, which took place on May 12, was the first time Portugal hosted the contest (3). There were three favorites to win: Israel, Norway, and Cyprus, with Israel ultimately taking the title (16, 19). There were also concerns about the host city's readiness and infrastructure (20). The event was a success, with high viewership and positive feedback (3, 13).
